All Parallelization Opportunities
Opportunity 1 — EDA Tasks: Parallel Code Generation (Easy Win)
Currently: 5 tasks, each does LLM call → execute → wait → next task.

What can be parallelized: The LLM code generation for all 5 tasks is completely independent — no task needs another task's code to generate its own code. You can fire all 5 LLM calls simultaneously:

# CURRENT (sequential)
for task in current_tasks:
    result = await code_agent.ainvoke(state)
# PROPOSED: Parallel code generation
code_generation_calls = [
    code_agent.nl_to_code(task["code_instruction"], history, state=state)
    for task in current_tasks
]
all_codes = await asyncio.gather(*code_generation_calls)
# Then execute sequentially (kernel constraint)
for code, task in zip(all_codes, current_tasks):
    result = kernel.execute(code)
Savings: 5 LLM calls at ~3-5s each = ~15-25s saved per cycle. With 2 cycles = ~30-50s.

Opportunity 2 — EDA Tasks: Fully Parallel Execution (Big Win, Complex)
The blocker today: All 5 EDA tasks share one Jupyter kernel (_get_code_agent() returns the same CodeAgent instance). Task 2 can use variables defined by Task 1 (df is still in memory). This is intentional — the code uses state["history"] to pass prior outputs as context.

Two approaches to fix this:

Approach 2A — Separate Kernel Per Task (Full Parallelism)
Give each task its own CodeAgent (its own Jupyter kernel). They are fully isolated.

async def execute_task_isolated(task, state):
    isolated_agent = CodeAgent()      # own kernel
    isolated_state = {**state}        # shallow copy
    isolated_state["history"] = []    # no shared history
    result = await isolated_agent.ainvoke(isolated_state)
    isolated_agent.executor.cleanup() # kill kernel after
    return result
results = await asyncio.gather(*[
    execute_task_isolated(task, state) for task in current_tasks
])
Trade-offs:

Saves 60-70% of EDA execution time
Each kernel startup costs ~5-15s (but this is in parallel so only counted once)
5 kernels × RAM per kernel = higher memory usage (~500MB total)
Tasks can't use each other's in-memory variables — each must reload the dataset from disk independently (not a real problem since domain_directory.json and .pkl files are on disk)
Approach 2B — Pre-load Datasets Once, Share via Files (Safer)
Load all datasets at the start of EDA, save them as parquet/feather files, have each parallel task read from those. This avoids re-reading .pkl files per task and gives each kernel a shared starting state via disk.

Opportunity 3 — Hypothesis Tests: Fully Parallel (Easiest Big Win)
This is the clearest parallelization opportunity in the entire codebase. The milestone metadata in the code itself already labels each hypothesis step as "dependency": "parallelizable":

                milestone_cb(f"Hypothesis: Test executed {hypothesis['id']}", "hypothesis_test_executed", {"hypothesis_id": hypothesis["id"], "dependency": "parallelizable", "is_llm_call": False})
Currently sequential:

